Khulubuse Zuma and Zondwa Mandela are expected to appear in the Springs magistrate's court today. * Editor's note: This article is updated each time new information becomes available. JOHANNESBURG - Aurora's former directors appeared briefly in the Springs magistrate's court on Wednesday. Magistrate Khensani Moila granted the defence's request for a postponement. The trial has now been rescheduled for 5 November. Khulubuse Zuma, Zondwa Mandela and Thulani Ngubane face charges under the National Water Act. READ: Khulubuse Zuma, Zondwa Mandela back in court They are accused of causing environmental and water transgressions. It's alleged they failed to treat underground water at the Grootvlei mine before releasing it into the Blesbokspruit River. In 2015, the Pretoria High Court found the trio personally guilty and liable for R1.7-billion in damages. This after more than 5,000 workers lost their jobs at the Aurora mine.